solution.p:
The LCD for the fractions is 8, so we build the first fraction:
    \dfrac{-3}{4} \cdot \alert{\dfrac{2}{2}} = \dfrac{-6}{8}
Then we combine like fractions:
    \dfrac{-6}{8}+\dfrac{5}{8} = \dfrac{-6+(-5)}{8} = \dfrac{-11}{8}

The LCD for the fractions is 12, so we build each fraction:
    \dfrac{-5}{6} \cdot \alert{\dfrac{2}{2}} = \dfrac{-10}{12};~~~~\dfrac{-3}{4} \cdot \alert{\dfrac{3}{3}} = \dfrac{-9}{12}
Then we combine like fractions:
    \dfrac{-10}{12}-(\dfrac{-9}{12}) = \dfrac{-10+9}{12} = \dfrac{-1}{12}

We multiply numerators together, and multiply denominators together:
    \dfrac{-2}{3}(\dfrac{5}{4}) = \dfrac{-2 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 4} = \dfrac{-10}{12}
Then we reduce:
    \dfrac{-10}{12} = \dfrac{-5 \cdot \cancel{2}}{6 \cdot \cancel{2}} = \dfrac{-5}{6}

We raise both sides to the reciprocal of the power.
        \begin{aligned}[t]
                (x^{0.24})^{1/0.24} \amp = (0.36\overline{1})^{1/0.24}\\
                 x \amp = 0.014                 
                \end{aligned}
        We evaluate (0.36\overline{1})^{1/0.24} by entering  ~~\text{ANS} ~\boxed{\wedge{}}~\boxed{~(~}~1~ \boxed{\div}~.24~\boxed{~)~}
